segments.text: He suggested, if I ask you this too, that a lot of people did pursue law around that time, though, because they were ineffective in combating the legal system through protest and such.
Would you agree with that?
Yes.
Also, are you a member of any radical-type lawyers' guild?
I'm a member of the National Lawyers' Guild and the American Civil Lawyers' Union.
I cooperate as an attorney representing people on those cases.
In fact, a few years ago, the Houston Police Department had a policy when they arrested someone of placing them on hold if they weren't quite sure what charges they were going to bring.
And they would keep people on this hold status, which was clearly unconstitutional sometimes for days.
And I've wrote a lawsuit.
as a cooperating attorney with the ACLU to stop this practice, to make them, within 24 hours, either charge someone or release them, and was successful in district court and federal court.
And the policy has since had to change because of that.
I think that the legal, I guess I'm involved in a few other types of cases like that.
It's a situation where
I think a lot of people turned to the legal system.
And in law school, I met a lot of people who were interested in doing that.
OK. Getting back to when you were suspended, how did that feel?
I mean, was there just complete hostility when they laid down?
Well, I was almost in a feeling of disbelief.
Like, are they really doing this over this?
Are they really suspending me for sitting on the grass?
It was an incredulous.
a feeling of, I can't believe this is happening.
I can't believe they're really doing this because I sat on the grass.
That was the initial reaction.
And how did it feel when you were let back in school three weeks later?
It felt great.
I mean, the attorney called with the news that the Fifth Circuit had agreed to let us back in school.
It felt good, like we'd been vindicated.
Or at least, initially, the courts thought that what we did wasn't so terrible.
And in fact, they even thought that we had some likelihood of prevailing on the merits.
And therefore, they were letting us back in school to finish.
What did your parents think when they found out?
They were happy I was being allowed back in school.
They were upset.
They were very upset that I was suspended.
They couldn't understand why I would do anything which would lead to a suspension.
They also saw it as one of ruining my career or future or that sort of thing, so it was very upsetting to me.
Who actually said you guys were after suspending?
The dean of students at that time, Floyd Martin, was the person who came with the rope.
The rope was held by the football team.
Oh gosh!
In fact, we had even a black football player right beside the dean holding the rope and telling us that that was it.
Where did everybody else go, these 3,000 people?
Well, I won't say there weren't 3,000 people at that point.
I'd say there must have been at least 200 on the grass.
But people decided they just weren't going to get suspended.
I mean, if the 3,000 were, I would say it would be a conservative estimate of what we had that night after the suspension.
And where did they meet?
It was at the administration library building, this huge area.
How did you get them together?
That was almost spontaneous.
Was it in anger because of the suspension?
Yeah, because of the suspension.
They just felt like that had gone too far.
And did y'all start chants or screaming?
There was chants.
There was a lot of screaming.
There was a lot of chanting.
I mean, it was just, it was a lot of people were very angry.
And how come the administration didn't come over there and try to do something else?
I don't know.
I just, I'm sure at that point they couldn't, you know.
They probably got a little scared.
Yeah, there was just too many people.
They just didn't know what was going to happen.

But, you know, on the actual, I mean, one of the noticed side here, Dean Martin, who was the one who read us the suspension letter, was subsequently fired from the university for stealing school funds.
And lost his job sometime in the, I think, late 70s or middle 70s.
was fired for, you know, stealing monies.
What were you thinking, though, when you were just sitting there on that grass, and there was just nine of you all there, and that's it, and here they come?
What was going through your head?
Well, of course, when they first came, it was still Phil.
And then when the dean read the letter saying, you've got three minutes to leave or you will be suspended, then a lot of people left.
But I had decided that I was not doing anything illegal, anything in violation of the law.
that I was exercising my constitutional right to free speech.
And I wasn't stopping or blocking anyone's path.
I wasn't doing anything like that.
And I couldn't believe that they'd really be doing this now.
My feeling is they're wrong, and I'm not going to let them get away with this.
I'm not going to let you get away with violating my rights.
And that was the feeling.
I've got a right to be doing this, and you're not going to stop me.
Were there any blacks in your little group?
There were some blacks in the demonstration, but the blacks at that time had their own organization.
And I think they were somewhat suspicious of the student mobilization committee.
It was predominantly white, and there was still a lot of uneasiness in that, and a lot of them had not joined it.
Your group, did they ever organize
march in support of civil rights?
Well, at that point, that never came up as an issue.
I mean, it wasn't a point at which some black student or black professor had been and had his rights violated or something.
None of those issues ever arose.
The issue of this foreign student came up, that he was Persian.
But the blacks seemed not to be very politically involved from the standpoint
uh, demonstration or protest.
They, most of the blacks seemed very much interested in making it or advancing in the system, scoring brownie points with the administration.
And so even their political organization was very limited in what it would do to challenge the administration or protest.
You mentioned, uh, threats and such.
Did those come after the second moratorium, after the first one, were reinstated in school?
They came, the threats came even before the first moratorium, but after the first they became more pronounced, and certainly after the second it was.
Although they were just mainly threats from people passing cars or things like that, it was never, you know, I was never beaten up.
At one point I was almost hit by a car, but seeing cars seem to be the way they like to do things in.
Never really had a, I had some confrontations where people would be trying to dare me to say if I'd do something or block my path on the street, but nothing more serious than that.
Ever any phone calls?
Yeah, there were phone calls.
What were you going to say?
We're going to get you.
We're going to kill you.
Get out of here, Yankee agitator.
Things like that.
The great thing, though, about the university system at that point was that if you didn't hang up the phone, you could trace the call.
I think that probably discouraged people from making those kind of phone calls.
Would you ever say anything back to them that you provoked in any way?
No, I wouldn't do anything, I wouldn't say anything to them.
In any confrontations, did you ever get to the point where you just wanted to provoke someone because they looked... No, I just knew.
I mean, I wanted to, but I didn't.
That was not the proven course to take.
along a very conservative line with your protest.
Yeah, as far as basically it was a nonviolent type approach.
And I felt that that was the best way to do it.
What did you think of the more violent type approaches, such as draft card burning, sit-ins?
Well, I thought sit-ins could at times be effective.
But I was aware of what we had at Southwest Texas State, that we couldn't give the police and the administration a chance
beat us up or arrest us because they would do it.
And I just thought that that was a step that we should not take.
And when you've been like sitting in New York or sitting in another large city, the results would have been much worse.
Your activism, especially when you got down to Southwest, was it an everyday thing?
Was it very intense?
Were you watching TV every day looking for the death counts or was it just
well, I need to work on this protest coming up.
How did you approach this?
No, I'd say it was fairly intense in that once we started getting things going, it was an almost daily.
I mean, almost some part of my day was spent planning or working with other people.
It was just almost an everyday thing.
And of course, then your whole social activities were less.
At some point, you were doing things relating to the organization or the demonstration.
Oh, I see.
What did you think of Nixon and LBJ then?
Well, you didn't like what Nixon said.
What did you think of both of those presidents back then and how you feel about them now?
Well, of LBJ, I thought that initially, you know, he was really concerned about social policy and really was trying to make a good attempt to improve the economic conditions in the country.
I think where he got sidetracked was thinking he could be both, you know, fight a war
I thought he was not properly informed by advisors, by intelligence estimates, of what was really happening in South Vietnam.
And I think the decisions he made were just tragic, because I think had he chosen to back out of Vietnam, the economic condition of the country could have greatly improved.
Unfortunately, he did not.
Yeah, I think that LBJ, I see him as being more of a person with genuine concern about people in the country, as opposed to Nixon that I see as being extremely cold and calculated.
Although I think LBJ, once he realized what had happened, he didn't have the courage to say, look, I've been wrong, which he could have done in 66 or 67 and just changed things around.
By the time the Tet Offensive, it was too late.
And then he had to withdraw from the candidacy.
But I think he didn't have the courage to really, in 66 or 67, just back out and change the policy.
I think he had gotten so involved in it that he couldn't do a turnaround, as he should have.
And it would have saved many lives and many problems that the country faced over the next several years.
What about Mr. Netzer?
I see him, I mean, you know, the term tricky dick just sums it all up.
I mean, he's just a person who's very cold, very calculating, a person who essentially was elected as someone who would probably end the war or be better equipped to end the war.
He campaigned in 68, and I've got this secret plan in my pocket, you know, I'll end this war, and then proceeded to escalate.
The thing is, he was just always a rabid anti-communist, always saw things in terms of communist versus anti-communist.
And I think he was a terrible leader for our country at that time because of that fact.
I mean, he was basically schooled in the 40s or late 40s type of containment communism.
I don't think that the man had the ability to really lead the country.
He was also very paranoid.
He saw every protest as someone who hated him.
It was a personal attack against him, because they were protesting his policies.
And you can't lead a nation with that kind of attitude, that kind of outlook.
And for that reason, I just found him repulsive.
And then, of course, he was a late alert.
He was also very crooked.
How'd you feel about that, the Watergate?
Well, I thought.
You know, it was to be expected.
I wasn't surprised by what he had done.
I was surprised that he finally got caught.
But I wasn't surprised by what he had done.
How did you feel with the invasion of Cambodia in 1970?
That, to me, was just outrageous.
I mean, I just, what I feared was that we'd be drawn into an even bigger war.
That instead of learning from what had been happening in the last several years in Vietnam, we were ignoring it.
And taking this, to me,
imbecilic approach of, well, we just conquer all of Southeast Asia.
The way to, we were still trying to win the war and thinking, well, if we just did more bombing, more weapons, somehow we'd win.
And to me, it was ludicrous.
Do you think that stems from the fact that they'd always won?
Yeah.
I think particularly Nixon was of this idea, America always wins a war.
And we'll do, obviously, we're not winning.
So rather than back out or just realize this is not
We had no business being here.
I mean, no one, neither Johnson nor Nixon, could ever admit, it was a mistake to be here.
Let's just get out.
We had to win.
And so you had Nixon's bombings and his ludicrous activities.
When you went back to City College in 1970, did you continue your career?
Yeah, I was involved in some anti-war activities.
Although, at that point, I guess,
It was a matter of being somewhat involved, but it wasn't the same, because there were lots of people involved in organizing activities.
There were always people willing to do things.
It wasn't like Southwest, where there wasn't someone to take on the leadership.
So you kind of sat back and participated.
I participated, but did not assume any, you know, was involved in some any war activities in organizing or participating in the organization of some.
Not to the extent that I did in San Marcos.
The students there at City College, were they aware of what you had done at Southwell?
Some were that I'd talked to, but I mean, nothing.
I mean, it was not.
I mean, the thing was, the kind of reaction was to me, they suspended you for that.
Just a look of disbelief.
When you were protesting and such, when you were organizing those groups of people to stand out against the war,
Did that give you any kind of sense of power?
And also, did you feel like you were accomplishing anything?

Well, I certainly felt like we were accomplishing something, that we were letting the community, the university, and hopefully the decision makers or policymakers in government realize that there was a significant sector that disagreed and disapproved their policies.
I mean, there was a sense of power in the sense of getting people
to organize or people to orchestrate this same belief that you had, this massive outpouring of feelings.

But I think it was less a feeling of power and more a feeling of accomplishment that we were getting a message across, or at least trying to, and at least having it heard or having a number of people show up to express the same
Did you say it was fun what you were doing, or was it more serious business?
It was serious.
I never felt like it was really fun.
I mean, sometimes it was a sense of satisfaction.
A lot of times, a sense of frustration.
Never quite fun.
Fun then was jumping out of airplanes.
It still is.
But it wouldn't really say fun.
a sense of satisfaction at times.
How did you, you had the S2 college deferment, but after you, did you just continue with that when you went to law school?

No, what happened was they instituted the lottery system in December of 70, or December of 69, and my number, while not being very high, by the time I finished, or the time my 2S deferment ran out, which was in 71,
they were not reaching my number, is basically what it came down to.
If you had been drafted, would you have gone?
No.
I would have applied for a conscientious objector status, and if not, would have refused.
Fortunately, I didn't have to come to that point, but I couldn't see myself going in the military.
What did you think of the people who did conform and get?
Well, it's kind of hard to judge them.
What distressed me was not so much the people who believed in what the government was doing and going, but the people who didn't want to go but went anyway.
I suppose I had less respect for them and felt that if everyone who had reservations about the Vietnam War would just speak out and refuse to go, they wouldn't have an army over there.
And that's what was distressing the people who just felt like, well, I've got to do this, even though I don't want to, even though I don't believe in what I'm doing.
And so we had a lot of people in Vietnam who didn't want to be there, didn't believe in what they were doing.
And that was distressing to me, that people would just go ahead and be pushed into that and allow themselves to be put in that situation.
I mean, I can intellectually understand why and what they were doing, but emotionally it was very upsetting.
Well, how did you feel when the troops were drawn?
I felt good about that.
I thought that was, unfortunately, just
too late.
I mean, it was satisfying that the government was finally doing it, but what seemed so sad was that the government didn't do it 10 years earlier.
Did you lose any friends?
I had one or two friends from my neighborhood in Brooklyn who were injured or killed in Vietnam.
How did you feel about that?
That was very upsetting.
Very, very upsetting.
Realizing it could be me or just the situation that it was all so needless.
Was your father in the service at all?
Yeah, he was in the Army, too.
Was he?
Did he see any acts of him?
Some in the Pacific.
Did you ever have any confrontations with him about your opinions?
No, I think my father, I think, and the, I guess after this happened, he had some understanding that I think he was beginning to, I think like a lot of adults or some adults,
in the question of what we were doing there, that this was a war that was just going on and on and on, and nothing was really happening.
And especially after the Tet Offensive, people began to say, why are we still there?
So we never had any real confrontations, but I think he began to understand my feelings.
In the demonstrations, the people that participated, they were mainly students, but you mentioned that some faculty and community members participated.
Did the administrators ever try to get anyone to speak, or was that just your thing, trying to get the faculty to speak?
The administration, did they ever offer to get people to speak?
No, they would have nothing to do with it.
And the community people, were they just business people?
Yeah, they were pretty much just business people who did not want to get involved.
The professors who spoke subsequently, some of them lost their jobs, except for the tenured ones.
But everyone who spoke who did not have tenure was subsequently lost.
And some professors I approached would not speak for fear of a process.
You mentioned in the interview you had a confrontation in a demonstration in May of 1970.
Is that at the vigil or is that something else?
That wasn't at the vigil.
The day of the vigil, which we had, we were going to lower the American flag, is what we had planned to do.
And we surrounded the flag by the Evans Academic Center.
And we're going to lower it to half-staff, or half-mast.
But then decided not to.
And instead, because what happened was the administration just sent down a lot of the cowboys to surround us.
And it looked like there was going to be a bloodbath or a fairly violent confrontation.
So at that point, we just sang a patriotic song and then invited anyone to discuss.
And there was a discussion that went on for about two hours between people.
Who started singing?
It was my idea at that point.
Really?
Because I realized they were looking for blood, and the administration was just going to look the other way.
Yeah.
I mean, they were clear.
one of the people in our group had a wire cutter that was going to lower the flag.
And I realized that if he did that, that would have just been violence.
Uh-huh.
And you said there were no arrests there because of the nonviolent activity?
That's right, there were not any.
That covers about everything that I wanted to
to dig into.
Is there anything else that you feel needs to be added in the statement you'd like to make?
Let me ask you this.
What do you think about our situation in Nicaragua right now?
I think it's a situation where we have no business being there.
I think we ought to let the whatever rebels in the government fight it out if
if that's what's going to be done there.

We should not, I just, I don't think we should be involved in supporting, it's just as wrong for us to be there supporting someone we like as it would be for us to be supporting someone we didn't like.
Or to be, it's wrong for us to criticize Russia for supplying weapons and supplies to one side as it is for us to be in there.
I mean, the government has always had this attitude that,
If the regime is pro-American, then it's okay for us to support them.
And I just find that difficult.
I don't agree with it.

And I still have a lot of problems with the government's policies, but I think that certainly after the Vietnam War, there seems to be, it's more acceptable for people to speak out, to organize, to protest.
I think the civil rights demonstrations of the early 60s, which was a forerunner of the late 60s,
But the difference was that you had large amounts of white youth involved in the 60s that you really did not in the early 60s in civil rights demonstrations.
I think people now accept that you can have demonstrations, you can protest.
I mean, back then, if you can imagine, it was very unusual, especially in San Marcos or a lot of smaller cities.
In Texas, in the South?
I'd say in the South and the Midwest.
It was very unusual.
I mean, we've become really conditioned to protest the demonstrations.
But in the late 60s, that was still something new, something unusual.
So I think that that's one benefit overall that's come out of that period, is that demonstrations and protests are acceptable.
just for civil rights demonstrations.
They're there for everybody with some sort of grievance or some sort of complaint about the government.
It's just more acceptable to do that.
I mean, back at that time, the middle to late 60s, that was not acceptable.
I mean, again, it was akin to being unpatriotic or seditious.
And that whole attitude has completely changed.
OK. Is there anything else you'd like to add?
No, I think that's enough.
That's plenty, believe me.
OK.
One of my.
